The area

Address
Neighborhood: Centrum
Amsterdams buzzing hub, with its sprawling network of tram rails and a seemingly constant flow of tourists and commuters, yields convenient access to some of the best sightseeing, shopping, and street life in Europe. Closest at hand are the Royal Palace, the quaint shops of Haalremmerdijk, the pedestrianized zones Kalverstraat and Dam Square with popular neighborhoods such as the Red Light District, and the Canal Ring hardly more than a moments stroll away. With the well-connected Centraal Station as Centrums base, it's easy to travel farther afield via one of the citys iconic trams.

    A unique museum in Amsterdam
    I went on a weekend trip to Amsterdam and didn't plan my stay. When I searched for interesting places near my hostel I found the pipe museum. Even as someone who just started pipe smoking it was a very interesting visit. I felt very welcome. The museum itself is a collection of pipes, there is nothing to read so someone was there to guide me. The tour through the small house was very interesting and the guide was very helpful in answering questions also talking about his own experiences and preferences concerning pipes which made the tour more of a dialogue which I really enjoyed. All in all I had a great time and would recommend ta visit. Since it is also very central and not a big museum you don't have to plan your whole day around it.
    Benedict G
    Right, you enumerate all advantages of our museum: not to big to stroll for ages, centrally located, interesting enough for anyone who is open to something new and unexpected. Thank you and ... be welcome!!

    Smoking my pipe
    I really enjoyed visiting the museum. The staff was very nice and friendly. My guide was a very professional young man. The diplay is very nice and also the house where the museum actually is. Poor customer service, or maybe for a much older crowd.
Oct 2023 Friends
A friend and I traveled to Amsterdam for vacation recently and visited as many museums we could in the short amount of time we were there. One of these museums was supposed to be the Pipe Museum. I now see the website mentions how the museum is hurting financially because of COVID. I suggest it is also because of the lack of customer service. My friend and I walked in and didn't even make it past the first few feet of the store when my friend spotted an interesting clay pipe display. He proceeded to take out his phone and snap a picture. Directly afterward an older man walked up to him and told him "no photos please" my friend told him he had seen photos all over the internet from the place. He was then told no photos unless asked first. Ok, maybe put a sign up about this loose policy?? We are in a time when appreciation is shown with photos, not to offend- especially, if there is NOT a sign requesting NO photos. What in the world.

We entered in the door that had a sign on it stating "Shop and Museum entrance" and thought we were following directions accurately. Toward the back of the shop there was a cash register and a visible stair case. My friend and I figured that was how to get to the museum, as most of the pipes in the basement had prices on them, we didn't think that was the museum. We walked toward the staircase in the back and were almost immediately accosted by the same older gentleman who says "Obey the sign please" and we both turn and see a red circle with a white line on it attached to a small red rope but with enough space to enter toward the back of the store. My friend then apologized (we both did NOT see this sign and were looking for the Pipe Museum entrance which is supposed to be through the basement according to the sign on the entrance door. My friend EXPLICITLY asked the guy, "How do we get to the museum?" and the guy tells us through the door outside next to the basement entrance. So apparently he blatantly lied to us INSTEAD of upselling the museum entrance fee!! What in the world?? My friend and I would have gladly paid the entrance fee, in cash as mentioned on the website. This had NOTHING to do with COVID and we won't be recommending the store or the phantom museum to other friends who visit the Netherlands.
Written November 5, 2023
